n, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Blaen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Blan  , or perhaps a shortened variant of the Suffolk surname <b>Blanden</b> (see   Blunden  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Blan","meanings":["English: variant of   Blann  .","French: variant of   Blanc   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]},{"name":"Cuch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Tyrone) and Scottish: variant of   McCosh  .","Americanized form of Polish   Kusz  , German   Kusch  , Czech <b>Kuš</b>, and Hungarian   Kus  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McCosh","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Coise</b> ‘son of <i>Cos</i>’, a byname meaning ‘messenger’ or ‘foot soldier’ from Irish Gaelic <i>cos</i> / Scottish Gaelic <i>cas</i> ‘foot, leg’."]}]},{"name":"Collwyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Modern: adoption of the Daffyd place name."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Collwyn ap Gwyn of Blaen Cuch was born about 0997, in Carmarthenshire, Wales. She married Collwyn